74–Deceased","1276–Female":"1276–Deceased","1279–Female":"1279–Deceased","1280–1347":"1280–1347","1228–Male":"1228–Deceased","1232–Female":"1232–Deceased","1274":"1274","1280":"1280","1228":"1228","Abt 1251":"about 1251","1347":"1347","1279":"1279","1255":"1255","1254":"1254","1232":"1232","1276":"1276","about 1279":"about 1279","about 1276":"about 1276","Abt 1280":"about 1280","about 1274":"about 1274","Brotton, , Yorkshire, England":"Brotton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Of Brotton, Yorkshire, England":"Brotton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Haunsard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): of Norman origin, from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Ansard</i> with prosthetic <i>H-</i>; from ancient Germanic <i>ans-</i> ‘(pagan) god’ + <i>ward</i> ‘guard, protector’ or <i>hard-</i> ‘brave, hardy’."],"variants":[{"name":"Hazard","meanings":["English: Anglo-Norman French variant of   Hansard  .","English and French: nickname from Old French, Middle English <i>hasard</i>, <i>hazard</i> ‘game of dice’, perhaps given to a player at hazard, i.e. a gambler, trickster, or rascal. The word probably derives from Arabic <i>az-zahr</i>, from <i>az</i>, assimilated form of the definite article <i>al</i>, + <i>zahr</i> ‘die’. It appears to have been picked up in the Holy Land and brought back to Europe by Provençal crusaders.","English: possibly in some instances of Flemish origin, a nickname from Middle Dutch <i>hasart</i> ‘hare’."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Matilda Haunsard was born in 1254, in Brotton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Robert Hansard, was 26 and her mother, Mrs Robert Hansard, was 23. She had at least 4 daughters with Robert de Thweng Lord of Kilton."},"et":{"1254–":"1254–Surnud","1254–Female":"1254–Surnud","1255–1279":"1255–1279","1274–Female":"1274–Surnud","1276–Female":"1276–Surnud","1279–Female":"1279–Surnud","1280–1347":"1280–1347","1228–Male":"1228–Surnud","1232–Female":"1232–Surnud","1274":"1274","1280":"1280","1228":"1228","Abt 1251":"umbes 1251","1347":"1347","1279":"1279","1255":"1255","1254":"1254","1232":"1232","1276":"1276","about 1279":"umbes 1279","about 1276":"umbes 1276","Abt 1280":"umbes 1280","about 1274":"umbes 1274","Brotton, , Yorkshire, England":"Brotton, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Of Brotton, Yorkshire, England":"Brotton, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United King